review_blob: From a can purchased in Brookline, NH. Just a very nice IPA - more citrus-y than the average New England IPA. Nicely astringent, good body. Good carbonation, as well - seems a bit more lively from the can than the bottle. Does that make sense?

This is a really nice beer - somehow the lagering mellows out the bitterness of the hops. Excellent mouth feel, excellent taste. As a New Englander, Im really glad to find a local IP(x) with a citrusy, not toasty, hopped flavor.

Interesting ale - reminds me of a malt liquor (although not nearly as sweet) - a lot of orange, more than grapefruit. Not as piney as a west coast strong IPA. As another reviewer said, hides its alcohol well. Very drinkable for a strong beer - sort of sneaky.
This was a great beer, and I miss it. It reminded me of New Amsterdam, the seminal New York microbrew from the 1980s (actually brewed by Matts upstate). Malty and hoppy but somehow balanced.
A nice bitter porter. Could have more substance. Slightly sour smell not apparent on tongue.
Some really nice grapefruit and other citric notes, but, as other raters have noted, a disappointing metallic finish. Tastes big for a Saranac.

Looks like Im an outlier here - this beer is sweet and a little musty, with a hint of iron oxide. Looks ok. Its a bottle I got from Yankee Spirits in Attleboro, MA in a case of assorted microbrews. Perhaps a bad batch.

I loved this beer, but seem to be the outlier. Cant realate to some of the other ratings - quality control? Different batches? Its true - it doesnt fit into any neat category, but a very good beer nonetheless. Bottled 4/2011, Batch 5. bottle #1808 - maybe its been improved since earlier batches. Poured a beautiful orange/amber, mildly citrusy/floral nose, faint Belgian hops, tasted and felt full in the mouth - sort of a Belgian IPA, where the sweetness and the yeast dampen some of the bittering hops. Just a good, perhaps sui generis beer. Bought after a tasting at Nikkis in Providence, RI.

On draft at Julians of Providence, RI. Beautiful brown beer, almost a Belgian imperial stout, with the sweetness and coffee notes of a stout and the spiciness and yeast flavors of a true Belgian. Excellent mouth feel, with no alcohol sting despite the high ABV. A wonderful beer.

A decent IPA - starts out better than it finishes. Medium bitter/floral/citrus nose and good initial burst of hops, but thins to a disappointing medicinal aftertaste. Not much mouth feel (and I do like mouth feel).

As my friend said, this Old German is part of a clever scheme. It has such a tinny aftertaste that you want to take another sip immediately to wash the aftertaste out of your mouth. This can go on for quite a while.
A very nice IPA - not as sweet as some, not overly bittered. Citrisy aroma. Could use a bit more of a malty feel - perhaps the higher alcohol level thins out the body.
Slightly malty, orange-y, nice mouth feel. As other posters have noted, high alcohol content is invisible to the palate. Overall a very pleasant beer, one I would drink again.

I think this is a fine beer, for a cheap mechanized American lager, with more than average body and flavor (again, for a cheap American etc. etc.). I had it in a 12-ounce can - I think some of the stuff you other guys were tasting in the 40s was each others saliva. I actually cheated on the appearance rating - Ive never actually seen it outside of a can (did I ever spill it? Not sure).

Looks better than it tastes.  Thin on the palate, not much nose. Not malty enough to justify the lack of hops. Im not good enough to taste the pecans and butterscotch, but I am usually put off by straw and this beer didnt have it. So Id drink it again, but wouldnt buy it.
